'''Imperial Starfighter Pilots''',<ref name="SWC">''[[Star Wars: Commander]]''</ref> also known as '''TIE fighter pilots'''<ref name="VG" /> or '''TIE pilots''',<ref name="Databank">{{Databank|tie-fighter|TIE fighter}}</ref> were an elite class within the [[Imperial Military|military]] of the [[Galactic Empire]]. They [[pilot]]ed the [[TIE series|TIE fighter series]] of starfighters, a line that included the [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter]], which was one of the Empire's most recognizable symbols of power, the [[TIE/sa tactical bomber|TIE/sa bomber]] and [[TIE/IN interceptor]].<ref name="Manual">''[[TIE Fighter Owners' Workshop Manual]]''</ref> There were two nicknames for TIE pilots: the vac-heads, who operated in [[Realspace|space]] for the Empire's [[Imperial Navy]], and the ground-hogs, who operated in [[planet]]ary [[atmosphere]] for the [[Imperial Army]]. Because the vac-heads had better public recognition through [[propaganda]] posters and the [[HoloNet News]] reports, the ground-hogs were often resentful of them. The rivalry between ground-hogs and vac-heads was so intense that most Imperial flight bases had separate [[Cantina|bars]] for the two groups, with the notable exception of the [[Bright Jewel Oversector Flight Base]].<ref name="LCZA" />

The precision and streamlined design of the TIE fighter was a source of pride for those pilots, who prided themselves for usually not needing [[deflector shield]]s or [[hyperdrive]]s, which they viewed as tools for the cowardly. Since TIE fighters were identical and interchangeable, TIE pilots might never fly the same ship twice and, as a result, rarely developed emotional ties to their craft.<ref name="VG" /> Nonetheless, they tended to be very protective of their vessel of the day, and loved to push around lower-ranked [[stormtrooper]]s. Very dedicated, TIE pilots were willing to surrender their lives for the greater glory of the Empire's [[New Order]].<ref name="RoR">''[[Rise of the Rebels]]''</ref> For this reason most TIE pilots had a life expectancy of less than a year.<ref name="Alphabet Squadron (novel)">[[Alphabet Squadron (novel)|''Alphabet Squadron'']]</ref>

TIE fighter pilots could also engage in surface combat, with [[Squad Five (Nar Shaddaa)|Squad Five]] participating in a [[Rescue of Luke Skywalker|skirmish]] on [[Nar Shaddaa]].<ref name="SW 12">[[Star Wars (2015) 12|''Star Wars'' (2015) 12]]</ref>

==Training==
{{Quote|The rebels are a desperate group of extremists. They'll fight with any ship, using any means necessary to undermine our authority. That is why orders must be followed without question. Insubordination like yours will get you and your wingman killed.|Vult Skerris, lecturing TIE pilot cadet "[[Sabine Wren|Ria Talla]]"|<ref name="The Antilles Extraction" />}}
[[File:AngledDeflectors-SWZ.png|thumb|left|220px|A TIE pilot in the cockpit of their fighter.]]
Graduates from prestigious flight academies across the galaxy underwent rigorous testing to become TIE pilots.<ref name="RO Visual Guide">''[[Star Wars: Rogue One: The Ultimate Visual Guide]]''</ref> Many TIE pilots received their training at [[Imperial Academy|Imperial Academies]] spread across the galaxy. Some of the best came out of the [[Royal Imperial Academy]] on [[Coruscant]] or the [[Skystrike Academy]] on [[Montross]], but other notable academies were located on [[Raithal]], [[Arkanis]], [[Carida]] and [[Corulag]].<ref name="Manual" /><ref name="The Antilles Extraction" /> In addition to the use of [[simulator pod]]s, [[cadet]]s would spend hundreds of flight hours piloting actual TIE fighters to hone their skills. Beyond piloting, cadets also receiving instruction in other fields including mathematics, science, hand-to-hand combat, and military strategy.<ref name="Manual" />

The final phase of testing often occurred onboard a larger battleship, such as a [[Star Destroyer]]. This was to expose cadets to realistic and relevant surroundings. During the [[Galactic Civil War]], TIE cadets often underwent literal trials by fire, plunged into combat situations where to excel was to survive.<ref name="RO Visual Guide" /> Of all the cadets who underwent the [[Imperial pilot training program]], ninety percent never graduated.<ref name="Manual" /><ref name="VG" /> As a consequence, those who did tended to be both proud and arrogant.<ref name="RO Visual Guide" />

[[File:TIEFighter4-CoverArt.jpg|thumb|right|250px|As the conflict with the rebellion heated up, TIE fighter pilots were thrown into battle as trails by fire.]]
TIE pilots underwent intense psychological conditioning that put completion of the mission above all other considerations, including their own life. Their training emphasized close coordination with their fellow pilots, as teamwork was considered the best way to accomplish their mission.<ref name="Manual" /> However, actually aiding their fellow pilots in an emergency was their lowest priority unless there was nothing else to do, since it was preferable to bring their full force against enemy fighters. All pilots were also expected to be able to repair and maintain all single- and dual-pilot craft.<ref name="Lost Stars" /> This included reassembling an [[ion engine]], reprograming their [[targeting computer]], and constructing a [[distress beacon]] out of wreckage.<ref name="Shadow Fall">''[[Shadow Fall: An Alphabet Squadron Novel]]''</ref>

Besides graduating from one of the academies, TIE pilots could be volunteers from one of the other organizations in the Imperial government, so long as they were certified pilots or astrogators.<ref name="Manual" /> [[Imperial Special Forces trooper]]s, such as the members of [[Inferno Squad]], wore gear similar to Imperial Starfighter Pilots. Indeed, [[Commander]] [[Iden Versio]] and her compatriots in Inferno Squad were equipped with enhanced TIE fighters.<ref name="Battlefront II">''[[Star Wars Battlefront II]]''</ref>
[[File:TIE Pilot Sideshow.png|thumb]]

==History==
The Imperial Starfighter Pilot class seen throughout much of the Imperial Era<ref name="A New Hope" /> succeeded the earlier [[conscription trooper pilot]]s<ref name="Confined Episode Guide">{{SW|url=series/the-bad-batch/confined-episode-guide|text="Confined" Episode Guide &#124; The Bad Batch}} {{C|Trivia Gallery Slide 6}}</ref> and [[clone trooper pilot]]s. The Empire had inherited the [[clone trooper]]-based [[Republic Military|military]] of the [[Galactic Republic]] that came before but worked to phase out those forces<ref name="Solitary Clone">{{TBB|The Solitary Clone}}</ref> under [[Project War-Mantle]].<ref name="War-Mantle">{{TBB|War-Mantle}}</ref> Although the Empire continued to make use of clones while they were useful,<ref name="Solitary Clone" /> [[TK stormtrooper]]s were introduced under War-Mantle as recruited soldiers who would replace the clones. Just as the citizen-recruited TK troopers paved the way<ref name="War-Mantle" /> for the finalized Imperial stormtrooper,<ref name="A New Hope" /> the conscription trooper pilots<ref name="Confined Episode Guide" /> were introduced as a new pilot class<ref name="Confined">{{TBB|Confined}}</ref> formed out of recruited citizens instead of cloned individuals and set the stage for the later Imperial Starfighter Pilot class.<ref name="Confined Episode Guide" /> Eventually, most clone troopers were phased out of active service due to their fast aging,<ref name="A New Dawn Panel">{{SW|url=news/sdcc-2014-star-wars-a-new-dawn-panel-liveblog|text=SDCC 2014: ''Star Wars: A New Dawn'' Panel – Liveblog}}</ref><ref name="Smuggler's Run">''[[Smuggler's Run: A Han Solo & Chewbacca Adventure]]''</ref> leaving the ranks of Imperial Starfighter Pilots to be formed out of recruited citizens trained in military academies.<ref name="The Antilles Extraction" />

==Equipment==
[[File:Flight_baron_Valen_Rudor.png|thumb|left|200px|Baron Rudor, with red stripes going down his helmet and sides, and white streaks below the eyes]]
TIE fighter pilots wore a self-contained, insulated [[Color|black]] [[TIE pilot flight suit]] with pockets and zip-front, a reinforced [[helmet]] reminiscent of the stormtrooper design, and chest armor featuring an emergency atmospheric unit and a life support pack.<ref name="Manual" /><ref name="RO Visual Guide" /> The [[flight suit]] was pressurized and constructed of energy-shielded fabric.<ref name="Manual" /><ref name="Encyclopedia">''[[Star Wars: The Visual Encyclopedia]]''</ref> The atmospheric [[control box]] on their flight suit was attached to two flexible [[gas]] transfer tubes that plugged into their vacuum-sealed [[Armor|helmet]]. The helmet was equipped with polarized lens and ship-linked displays and communications.<ref name="Manual" /><ref name="VG" /> On TIE pilot belts, to their right of their belt-buckle was a comlink/transponder in a shockproof case. TIE pilots also wore positive-gravity pressure [[boot]]s and insulated [[gauntlet]]s.<ref name="RO Visual Guide" /> [[Imperial Special Forces trooper]]s wore uniforms similar in design to TIE fighter pilots.<ref name="Battlefront II">''[[Star Wars Battlefront II]]''</ref>

The gear of [[AT-AT pilot]]s was similar in design to that of Imperial Starfighter Pilots.<ref name="2020AT-ATCard">{{Topps|set=2020 Topps Star Wars Masterwork|subset=Troopers of the Galactic Empire|cardname=Imperial AT-AT Pilot|link=https://www.tcdb.com/ViewCard.cfm/sid/253067/cid/15634566}}</ref> TIE pilots could be equipped with an [[E-11 medium blaster rifle]]<ref name="SW 12" /> or a [[blaster pistol]].<ref name="TIE Fighter 3">[[TIE Fighter 3|''TIE Fighter'' 3]]</ref> Some helmets had white stripes below the [[eye]]s,<ref name="A New Hope">{{Film|IV}}</ref> and some elite pilots such as [[Baron of the Empire|Baron]] [[Valen Rudor]] and [[Captain]] [[Vult Skerris]] had red or yellow stripes going down the middle of their helmets and sides.<ref name="The Antilles Extraction" /><ref name="Empire Day">{{Rebels|Empire Day (episode)}}</ref> The [[Sienar test pilot|Imperial test pilots]] who flew experimental craft for [[Sienar Fleet Systems]]<ref name="One Year">{{Andor|One Year Later}}</ref> were known as "Sienar test pilots"<ref name="Figure">{{HasbroCite|set=Star Wars: The Black Series|packtype=''Star Wars: Andor'' Figure|pack=#15: Cassian Andor (Sienar Test Pilot)|link=product/star-wars-the-black-series-cassian-andor-sienar-test-pilot/G15535X00}}</ref> and donned their own variant of the TIE pilot uniform, featuring a unique helmet and partially red clothing.<ref name="One Year" /> TIE pilot jumpsuits were taken by the [[Uprising]] for its stolen TIEs, creating the [[Uprising TIE pilot]] class.<ref name="Uprising TIE pilot">''[[Star Wars: Uprising]]''&mdash;Crew Member: "Uprising TIE pilot"</ref>

==Behind the scenes==
''[[Ultimate Star Wars]]'' first identified TIE fighter pilots as "human" in [[2015]].<ref name="Ultimate" /> [[Star Wars Helmet Collection 6|''Star Wars Helmet Collection'' 6]], released in [[2016]], stated that they were "various, mostly human," implying the existence of non-human pilots.<ref name="HC6">[[Star Wars Helmet Collection 6|''Star Wars Helmet Collection'': TIE Fighter Pilot]]</ref> However, ''[[Ultimate Star Wars, New Edition]]'', released in [[2019]], stated "human" again.<ref name="USWNE">''[[Ultimate Star Wars, New Edition]]''</ref> This is also stated in later sources, such as ''[[Star Wars Encyclopedia: The Comprehensive Guide to the Star Wars Galaxy]]'',<ref name="Complete Encyclopedia">''[[Star Wars Encyclopedia: The Comprehensive Guide to the Star Wars Galaxy]]''</ref> and the Character Encyclopedias.<ref name="Character Encyclopedia 2016">''[[Star Wars Character Encyclopedia: Updated and Expanded]]''</ref><ref name="Character Encyclopedia 2019">''[[Star Wars Character Encyclopedia, New Edition]]''</ref><ref name="Character Encyclopedia 2021">''[[Star Wars: Character Encyclopedia, Updated and Expanded Edition]]''</ref> As ''Star Wars Helmet Collection'' magazines do not explicitly credit the [[Lucasfilm Story Group]], then information from ''Ultimate Star Wars'' and ''Ultimate Star Wars, New Edition'', which both have Story Group credits, take precedence.

